Costa Rica's strategic location in Central America, its role in regional politics, and its economic ties to the United States make the ambassador's role more than ceremonial. Issues such as trade, drug trafficking, environmental cooperation, and regional security often feature prominently on the agenda. The ambassador is, in effect, the face of the United States in a country that, despite its small size, punches above its weight in international diplomacy and environmental advocacy.

